  <static seed="74" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddFractions70.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{-\frac{5}{6} + \frac{8}{9}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="10" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{1}{18}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add two fractions with different denominators, we first have to find a common denominator.</p>
<p>In this case, the least common multiple of <m>6</m> and <m>9</m> is <m>18</m>.</p>
<p>Look at the first fraction <m>\displaystyle{-\frac{5}{6}}</m>. To change the denominator to <m>18</m>, we multiply <m>3</m> at both the top and bottom, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned} -\frac{5}{6} \amp = -\frac{5 \cdot 3}{6 \cdot 3}\\ \amp = -\frac{15}{18} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>Similarly, we change the second fraction<rsq/>s denominator to <m>18</m>:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{8}{9} \amp = \frac{8 \cdot 2}{9 \cdot 2}\\ \amp = \frac{16}{18} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>Now we can add those two fractions. The full process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   -\frac{5}{6} + \frac{8}{9}
        \amp = -\frac{15}{18} + \frac{16}{18} \\
        \amp = \frac{-15 + 16}{18} \\
        \amp = \frac{1}{18}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer to this question is  <m>\displaystyle{\frac{1}{18}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
